I have everything I need. The knowledge graph is complete and unambiguous. Here's the full diagnosis.

---

## Diagnosis

The cap-height of your serif glyphs is clipped at the top of the display-scale title input, and bumping `padding-top` makes the input taller but doesn't fix it. That's the exact failure signature documented in **AP-064** / **EAP-077** / **ENG-139**: you are fighting a browser-level constraint that CSS padding cannot solve.

---

## Root Cause

**AP-064 · EAP-077 (active — cited in FB-129 and ENG-139)**

The problem has two independent layers:

### Layer 1 — `<input>` clips its own text area at the content edge
A native `<input type="text">` positions its internal text cursor at the **top of the content rectangle** — the area bounded by `padding-edge`, not the full box. The browser's text renderer places the first pixel of the **ascender** (which for a display-scale serif like IBM Plex Serif at 2.5–3.5 rem can reach well above the cap-height) flush against the top padding edge. When the computed padding-top is too small — or even at zero — those ascending pixels are painted **outside the content box** and the browser composites them against the background *within the element's overflow clip*. `<input>` has a UA stylesheet rule equivalent to `overflow: hidden` on its internal text layer, which it applies to its own text node before your CSS even runs. **You cannot override this with `padding-top` because the clip is applied at the rendering layer, not the layout layer.**

### Layer 2 — `overflow: hidden` on a containing ancestor (secondary cause)
EAP-080 documents the compounding case: if any ancestor also has `overflow: hidden` (common on editor wrappers that need to constrain Lexical's floated toolbars), that creates a second paint clip that truncates any glyphs which escaped the `<input>`'s own clip via a transform or stacking context promotion. This is documented in ENG-141 as a regression vector.

### Why `padding-top` doesn't help
Increasing `padding-top` shifts the text's **layout** position down inside the box, but the browser's internal UA text-clip for `<input>` still fires at whatever the content-box top happens to be. The glyph's ascender paint origin moves down by the same amount as the padding, so it remains perpetually at the clip boundary. You are moving the floor, but the ceiling moves with it.

---

## Fix

The canonical fix (per AP-064 correct alternative, verified in the login page fix FB-129 → ENG-139) is **to stop using `<input>` for display-scale text** and replace it with a `<div contentEditable>` or `<textarea>` (for multi-line) whose overflow model you fully control.

### Step 1 — Replace `<input>` with `contentEditable` in the editor component

Find the case-study editor's display-scale title field. Based on the field split documented in FB-106 / CFB-026, this is almost certainly the `introBlurbHeadline` field rendered by a custom Payload admin component under `src/` (the inline-edit path).

**Before — the broken pattern:**
```tsx
// src/components/admin/CaseStudyEditor/DisplayTitleInput.tsx  (or similar)
<input
  type="text"
  className={styles.displayTitle}        // e.g. 3rem IBM Plex Serif
  value={value}
  onChange={(e) => onChange(e.target.value)}
/>
```

**After — the correct pattern:**
```tsx
// src/components/admin/CaseStudyEditor/DisplayTitleInput.tsx
"use client"
import { useRef, useEffect } from "react"
import styles from "./DisplayTitleInput.module.scss"

interface Props {
  value: string
  onChange: (v: string) => void
  placeholder?: string
}

export function DisplayTitleInput({ value, onChange, placeholder }: Props) {
  const ref = useRef<HTMLDivElement>(null)

  // Sync external value into the div without clobbering cursor position
  useEffect(() => {
    const el = ref.current
    if (!el || el.textContent === value) return
    el.textContent = value
  }, [value])

  return (
    <div
      ref={ref}
      role="textbox"
      aria-multiline="false"
      contentEditable
      suppressContentEditableWarning
      className={styles.displayTitle}
      data-placeholder={placeholder ?? "Case study title"}
      onInput={(e) => {
        onChange((e.currentTarget as HTMLDivElement).textContent ?? "")
      }}
      onKeyDown={(e) => {
        // Prevent newlines — this is a single-line title field
        if (e.key === "Enter") {
          e.preventDefault()
        }
      }}
    />
  )
}
```

### Step 2 — Write the SCSS module with glyph-safe padding

The key property is `padding-block` (or `padding-top`/`padding-bottom`) set to a value that gives the ascender room **above** the content edge. For IBM Plex Serif at display scale (~2.75–3.5 rem), the ascender extends roughly 30% above the cap-height, which itself is ~70% of the em-square. The safe rule of thumb from the documented fix is: **use `0.15em` to `0.2em` padding-block-start**. This is em-relative so it scales with any font-size change.

Additionally — and this is the key structural difference from body-scale text — you must ensure **no ancestor** has `overflow: hidden` without a compensating inset.

```scss
// src/components/admin/CaseStudyEditor/DisplayTitleInput.module.scss
.displayTitle {
  // Typography
  font-family: var(--font-plex-serif), "IBM Plex Serif", Georgia, serif;
  font-size: $portfolio-type-display;      // e.g. 2.75rem or 3rem token
  font-weight: $portfolio-weight-light;
  line-height: 1.1;
  color: $portfolio-text-primary;

  // Glyph-safe vertical clearance
  // 0.15em at 2.75rem = ~6.6px — enough for Plex Serif ascenders + diacritics
  padding-block-start: 0.15em;
  padding-block-end: 0.1em;
  padding-inline: 0;                        // flush with the column grid

  // Critical: contentEditable must NOT clip its own overflow
  overflow: visible;

  // Single-line constraint (matches the <input> behavior being replaced)
  white-space: nowrap;
  overflow-x: hidden;       // allow horizontal scrolling without clipping ascenders
  overflow-y: visible;      // ← this is the operative line; vertical must stay visible

  // Placeholder via CSS attr()
  &:empty::before {
    content: attr(data-placeholder);
    color: $portfolio-text-tertiary;
    pointer-events: none;
  }

  // Engagement ring (matches AP-054 canonical pattern — box-shadow, not border-width)
  outline: none;
  border-bottom: $portfolio-border-width-thin solid transparent;

  &:focus {
    border-bottom-color: $portfolio-text-primary;
    // +1px visual weight via shadow ring without changing layout
    box-shadow: 0 1px 0 0 $portfolio-text-primary;
  }
}
```

### Step 3 — If an ancestor wrapper has `overflow: hidden`, add glyph clearance

```scss
// The editor wrapper that encloses the title input
.editorHeader {
  // If overflow: hidden is truly needed here (e.g. to clip a Lexical toolbar):
  overflow: hidden;

  // Add inset padding equal to the glyph escape zone at the top
  // so ascenders paint inside the clip boundary
  padding-block-start: 0.2em;  // matches displayTitle padding-block-start
}
```

---

## What's structurally different about display-scale fonts in inputs

This is the core of AP-064 and worth understanding precisely:

| Property | Body scale (0.875–1rem) | Display scale (2.5–3.5rem) |
|---|---|---|
| **Ascender height above cap** | ~2–3px absolute | ~8–14px absolute |
| **`line-height: 1.1` air above text** | ~1–2px | ~3–6px |
| **UA `<input>` text-layer clip** | Invisible — ascenders fit within normal padding | **Visible** — ascender overshoots any sane padding value |
| **`padding-top` fixes it?** | Yes, usually | No — the clip moves with the content box |
| **em-relative padding still safe?** | Yes | **Yes, but must be ≥ 0.15em and applied to `contentEditable`, not `<input>`** |
| **`overflow-y: visible` required?** | No | **Yes — must be explicit on the host element** |

The em-square of a font contains the full ascender + descender envelope. At body scale, browsers have generous UA padding on `<input>` that incidentally fits the ascender. At display scale, the absolute size of the ascender (IBM Plex Serif Light has a very tall, bracketed ascender) exceeds what any reasonable `padding-top` value can push the baseline down far enough to keep visible — because the browser clips `<input>`'s text layer at the content box, not at the glyph bounding box. `contentEditable` on a block element has no such UA clip; its overflow is governed entirely by CSS, which you control.

---

## Principle

> **Never use `<input type="text">` for display-scale (≥ 2rem) serif text.** The browser's internal text-clip on `<input>` fires at the content-box edge before your CSS runs. Replace with `<div contentEditable>`, set `overflow-y: visible` explicitly, and use `padding-block-start: 0.15em` (em-relative, so it scales). Never set `overflow: hidden` on a direct ancestor of a display-scale text element without adding equivalent inset compensation. — AP-064, EAP-077, EAP-080
